Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working on the marketing analyst team at Bellabeat, a high-tech manufacturer of health-focused products for women. Bellabeat is a successful small company, but they have the potential to become a larger player in the global smart device market. Urka Sren, cofounder and Chief Creative Officer of Bellabeat, believes that analyzing smart device fitness data could help unlock new growth opportunities for the company. You have been asked to focus on one of Bellabeats products and analyze smart device data to gain insight into how consumers are using their smart devices. The insights you discover will then help guide marketing strategy for the company. You will present your analysis to the Bellabeat executive team along with your high-level recommendations for Bellabeats marketing strategy.

About the company

Urka Sren and Sando Mur founded Bellabeat, a high-tech company that manufactures health-focused smart products. Sren used her background as an artist to develop beautifully designed technology that informs and inspires women around the world. Collecting data on activity, sleep, stress, and reproductive health has allowed Bellabeat to empower women with knowledge about their own health and habits. Since it was founded in 2013, Bellabeat has grown rapidly and quickly positioned itself as a tech-driven wellness company for women.

By 2016, Bellabeat had opened offices around the world and launched multiple products. Bellabeat products became available through a growing number of online retailers in addition to their own e-commerce channel on their website. The company has invested in traditional advertising media, such as radio, out-of-home billboards, print, and television, but focuses on digital marketing extensively. Bellabeat invests year-round in Google Search, maintaining active Facebook and Instagram pages, and consistently engages consumers on Twitter. Additionally, Bellabeat runs video ads on Youtube and display ads on the Google Display Network to support campaigns around key marketing dates.

Sren knows that an analysis of Bellabeats available consumer data would reveal more opportunities for growth. She has asked the marketing analytics team to focus on a Bellabeat product and analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how people are already using their smart devices. Then, using this information, she would like high-level recommendations for how these trends can inform Bellabeat marketing strategy.

Ask

Sren asks you to analyze smart device usage data in order to gain insight into how consumers use non-Bellabeat smart devices. She then wants you to select one Bellabeat product to apply these insights to in your presentation.

These questions will guide your analysis:

-What are some trends in smart device usage?
-How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?
-How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Importing datasets that I will be analyzing

dailyactivitymarch <- read_csv('dailyActivity_mergedmarch.csv')
dailyactivityapril <- read_csv('dailyActivity_mergedapril.csv')
sleep <- read_csv('sleepDay_merged.csv')
steps <- read_csv('hourlySteps_merged.csv')

str(dailyactivitymarch)
str(dailyactivityapril)
str(steps)
str(sleep)

Cleaning up the data

Removing duplicates, NAs, and unnecessary columns

dailyactivitymarch <- dailyactivitymarch%>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  select(-LoggedActivitiesDistance, -TrackerDistance)
  
dailyactivitymarch <- dailyactivitymarch %>% 
  filter(TotalDistance > 0.5)
  
dailyactivityapril <- dailyactivityapril%>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct() %>% 
  select(-LoggedActivitiesDistance, -TrackerDistance) %>% 
  filter(TotalDistance > .5)

sleep <- sleep %>% 
  distinct()

steps <- steps %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  distinct()

Combing daily activity tables into one

dailyactivity <- bind_rows(dailyactivitymarch, dailyactivityapril)

Changing timestamp from chr to date, need to put into POSIXct first to be able to pull both time and date separately

dailyactivity$ActivityDate = as.POSIXct(dailyactivity$ActivityDate, format = '%m/%d/%Y')
dailyactivity$Date <- format(dailyactivity$ActivityDate, format = '%m/%d/%Y')

Changing time format so that we can split date from hour

steps <- steps %>% 
  mutate(
    Date = format(mdy_hms(ActivityHour, tz = Sys.timezone())),
    Time = format(mdy_hms(ActivityHour, tz = Sys.timezone())), '%H:%M:%S')

Formatting date from yyyy-dd-mm, to mm/dd/yyyy and removing original ActivityHour column

steps <- steps %>% 
  mutate(Date = as.Date(Date))
steps <- steps %>% 
  mutate(Date = format(Date, '%m/%d/%Y'))
steps <- steps %>% 
  select(-ActivityHour)

Making a column TotalActiveMinutes from the dailyactivity DF

dailyactivity <- dailyactivity %>% 
  mutate(TotalActiveMinutes = VeryActiveMinutes + FairlyActiveMinutes + LightlyActiveMinutes)

Making a column for hours asleep

sleep <- sleep %>% 
  mutate(TotalHoursAsleep = round(TotalMinutesAsleep / 60, 1))

Renaming column to HourlyStep Total from Step Total

steps <- steps %>% 
  mutate(HourlyStepTotal = StepTotal)
steps <- steps %>% 
  select(-StepTotal)

Making sedentary hours column

dailyactivity <- dailyactivity %>% 
  mutate(SedentaryHours = SedentaryMinutes / 60)
dailyactivity$SedentaryHours <- round(dailyactivity$SedentaryHours, digits = 1)

Making total active hours column

dailyactivity <- dailyactivity %>% 
  mutate(TotalActiveHours = TotalActiveMinutes / 60)
dailyactivity$TotalActiveHours <- round(dailyactivity$TotalActiveHours, digits = 1)

According to a study by BMC Public Health (https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5397769/), the average woman takes 4,912 steps per day, which is roughly just over 2 miles. The numbers in this dataset represent an above average group, as the 1st quartile is already above the average steps per day of women, as well as the total distance. This data is biased in that it only measure the steps of women in the United States.

However a study published by Medicine and Science in Sports and Exercise (https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34310489/) shows that in 2019, the average hours spent being sedentary was 9.5 hours. Again, this dataset represents an above average group when it comes to this measure.

This dataset isnt the most reliable as it only measure 35 participants, and the sample size is not enough to develop any real conclusions. We also dont know the age of the participants which would make a big difference in understanding their fitness patterns.

Creating day of the week column to make a chart comparing total steps by day of week

dailyactivity$DayOfWeek <- wday(dailyactivity$ActivityDate, label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)
dailyactivity <- dailyactivity %>% select(Id, Date, ActivityDate, DayOfWeek, everything())

#removing ActivityDate
dailyactivity <- dailyactivity %>% select(-ActivityDate)

Creating AvgStepsDay column to put in plot

dailyactivity <- dailyactivity %>% 
  group_by(DayOfWeek) %>% 
  mutate(AvgStepsDay = mean(TotalSteps, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ungroup()
dailyactivity$AvgStepsDay <- round(dailyactivity$AvgStepsDay, digits = 0)

Plot of AvgStepsDay by Day of Week

ggplot(dailyactivity, aes(x = DayOfWeek, y = AvgStepsDay, fill = AvgStepsDay))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')+
  geom_text(aes(label = AvgStepsDay), vjust = -0.5)+
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,max(dailyactivity$AvgStepsDay) *1.1))+
  labs(title = "Average Steps Per Day of Week", x = "Day of Week", y = "Avg Steps/Day")

What days of the week have the highest and lowest activity?

-Not too much difference, but you can see Saturday has a slight uptick, while Sunday has less steps than average. This can be used as a motivation notification through the app to Not have a lazy Sunday! You can see it looks like there is a slight de-motivation as the week progresses into the weekend. Maybe the marketing team can take these numbers and run a campaign saying to treat every day like Monday. Dont lose the motivation throughout the week, you want to earn the weekend!

Plot for calories burned compared to sedentary minutes

ggplot(data = dailyactivity) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = SedentaryMinutes, y = Calories, color = TotalActiveMinutes))+
  scale_color_distiller(palette = "YlOrRd")+
  labs(title = "Calories Burned compared to Sedentary Minutes", x = "Sedentary Minutes", y = "Calories Burned", color = "Total Active Minutes") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", aes(x = SedentaryMinutes, y = Calories))

How does being sedentary affect calories burned?
Surprisingly, as seen in the chart below, there doesnt seem to be a real correlation between minutes spent being sedentary and calories burned.

How does being active affect calories burned?
There is clearly a correlation between Active Minutes and Calories Burned. Need to promote more activity if people want to lose weight and be healthier.

Adjusting SleepDay to correct time format so I can merge with dailyactivity

sleep <- sleep %>%
  mutate(SleepDay = as.POSIXct(SleepDay, format = "%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p"))
sleep <- sleep %>% 
  mutate(SleepDay = format(SleepDay, '%m/%d/%Y'))

#merge dailyactivity and sleep tables
sleep <- sleep %>% 
  rename(Date = SleepDay)
dailysleep <- merge(dailyactivity, sleep, by = c('Id', 'Date'))

Sleep Insights

Plotting Calories Burned and Total Hours Sleep

ggplot(dailysleep, aes(x=Calories, y=TotalHoursAsleep, color = TotalHoursAsleep))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")+
  labs(title = "Do Sleep Patterns affect Calorie Burn?", x='Calories Burned', y='Hours of Sleep per Night')

There doesnt seem to be much of a correlation between hours of sleep per night and calories burned. As you can see the people that get more than 10 hours of sleep seem to burn between 1500-2000 calories a day. What is surprising is that people getting 2.5 hours of sleep per night or less seem to burn between 1500-4000 calories. This could be people working two jobs where they are constantly being active and work late into the night.

I would recommend advising people about sleeping habits and how sleeping more than 10 hours a day leads to less caloric burn than is recommended for a healthy lifestyle

Plot showing sedentary minutes per day and hours of sleep per night

ggplot (dailysleep, aes(x = TotalHoursAsleep, y = SedentaryMinutes, color = TotalHoursAsleep))+
  geom_point()+
  scale_color_gradient(low = 'red', high = 'blue')+
  labs(title = 'Minutes Sedentary vs Sleeping Hours per Night', x='Hours of Sleep/Night', y='Sedentary Minutes/Day')+
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', color = 'black')

We have a clear correlation between Sedentary Minutes per Day and Hours of Sleep/Night. The more time spent being sedentary during the day, the chart shows it is likely to lead to less hours of sleep per night. This can be a great opportunity to motivate consumers to be more active if they want to achieve a healthy sleep cycle

Overall recommendations for Bellabeat

Through all this data you can see some clear patterns, however I believe the dataset is too small to make any real marketing recommendations. I also think not having the age of the participants is a big factor and can really skew this data.
Sample size:
-35 participants in the daily activity data set
-24 participants in the sleep statistics data set
-33 participants in the steps data set

  • According to this data, I would recommend promoting a less sedentary lifestyle, as the numbers from participants in this study were pretty concerning compared to official recommendations in both areas. They are doing great with Total Steps though, so I would make it known that Bellabeat customers seem to have way more steps than the average woman.

  • I would send out daily motivations as we know throughout the week, participants daily step counts tend to decrease as the week progresses to Saturday.

  • Do more to educate users on how much activity is needed to burn specific amounts of calories, as this is the best way to a healthier lifestyle.

  • Inform users about sleep patterns, and how getting more than 10 hours of sleep per day can lead to less calories burned daily. Promote targeting a healthy 7-9 hours of sleep a day.

  • Motivate users to be more active to achieve a healthy sleep cycle, as there is a strong correlation between sedentary minutes and hours sleeping.
